---
import MarketingLayout from '../../../layouts/MarketingLayout.astro';
import { canonicalUrl } from '../../../lib/seo/site';
import { routeMap } from '../../../lib/i18n/routes';

const pathname = '/en/privacy-policy/';
const title = 'Privacy policy - get2software.com';
const description =
  'Privacy information for get2software.com: how to reach the controller, what data may arise, why it is processed, retention, subprocessors, cookies, and your rights.';
---

<MarketingLayout
  locale="en"
  title={title}
  description={description}
  pathname={pathname}
  hreflangPl={canonicalUrl(routeMap.privacy.pl)}
  hreflangEn={canonicalUrl(pathname)}
  alternateHref={routeMap.privacy.pl}
>
  <!--
    Section order differs from a typical “definitions-first” template: contact and scope up front, glossary last.
    Wording is written for this site only (marketing pages + optional contact form).
  -->
  <div class="g2-container max-w-3xl py-14 md:py-20">
    <h1 class="g2-heading-xl">Privacy policy</h1>
    <div class="g2-prose mt-8 space-y-6">
      <p>
        This page explains how personal data may be processed when you use the website <strong>get2software.com</strong>{' '}
        (the <strong>“Site”</strong>). It covers browsing the published pages and contacting us (via the contact form
        when enabled, or by email). The text is written specifically for this Site and only describes the processing
        activities mentioned here.
      </p>

      <h2 class="font-display text-xl font-semibold text-g2-text">Who is responsible and how to reach us</h2>
      <p>
        The controller of personal data under the GDPR (Regulation (EU) 2016/679) is the organisation responsible for
        operating the <strong>get2software.com</strong> Site, identifiable from its public registration and contact
        details.
      </p>
      <p>
        For privacy questions, email{' '}
        <a href="mailto:kontakt@get2software.com" class="text-g2-accent hover:underline">kontakt@get2software.com</a>. A
        short subject line (for example “data correction request” or “question about logs”) helps us route the message
        without unnecessary back-and-forth.
      </p>

      <h2 class="font-display text-xl font-semibold text-g2-text">Who this notice is for</h2>
      <p>In practice, this notice matters if you are:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          a visitor loading Site pages — which may generate limited technical data as part of normal web delivery and
          security controls;
        </li>
        <li>
          someone contacting us about cooperation or products — through the contact form (when available), email, or
          phone in a business context.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        We do not operate a newsletter or webinar registration through this Site as a separate product line. If we add
        data-heavy features later, we will publish an updated description (or a dedicated notice) before relying on new
        processing.
      </p>

      <h2 class="font-display text-xl font-semibold text-g2-text">What kinds of data may exist</h2>
      <p>The categories depend on what you do:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Contact-related content</strong> — such as company name, email address, phone number, subject, message
          body, and anything else you choose to include;
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Technical metadata</strong> — such as IP address, timestamps, browser hints, server diagnostic lines, and
          security-related identifiers tied to bot protection for the form (exact fields depend on production
          configuration).
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="font-display text-xl font-semibold text-g2-text">Why we process data and the legal bases</h2>
      <p>
        <strong>Running the Site safely.</strong> Delivering pages, diagnosing faults, and reducing abuse — Article 6(1)(f)
        GDPR (legitimate interests in operating a dependable website).
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Answering your message.</strong> Handling correspondence and preparing follow-up materials — Article
        6(1)(f) GDPR; where a consent checkbox is required for a specific step, Article 6(1)(a) GDPR also applies to that
        step.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Protecting the contact form.</strong> Short checks with a third-party vendor to reduce automated spam —
        Article 6(1)(f) GDPR.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Claims and legal duties.</strong> Retention where needed to establish, exercise, or defend legal claims, or
        to meet statutory obligations — Article 6(1)(f) and/or Article 6(1)(c) GDPR, depending on the situation.
      </p>

      <h2 class="font-display text-xl font-semibold text-g2-text">Where the data comes from</h2>
      <p>
        Most information comes directly from you (typed into the form or written in an email). A smaller portion is
        created automatically by the infrastructure that hosts the Site, because a public website cannot function without
        basic request handling and logging.
      </p>

      <h2 class="font-display text-xl font-semibold text-g2-text">How long we keep information</h2>
      <p>
        We keep contact content for as long as needed to finish the conversation, then for any additional period required
        for limitation periods or statutory record-keeping, if applicable. When the purpose ends, we delete or anonymise
        data unless law requires longer storage.
      </p>
      <p>
        Technical log retention is governed by our hosting and security vendors’ policies and is often shorter than the
        retention window for commercial correspondence.
      </p>

      <h2 class="font-display text-xl font-semibold text-g2-text">Who may process data on our behalf</h2>
      <p>
        We use external services that are necessary to publish the Site and deliver messages. Sharing is limited to what
        those services need to perform their task. Typical examples include:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>hosting or cloud infrastructure serving Site files;</li>
        <li>
          an endpoint that accepts form submissions (for example an edge function) plus a transactional email provider
          that delivers the message;
        </li>
        <li>a vendor providing bot/human verification for the form;</li>
        <li>legal or IT advisers, only when a matter requires it.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>We use data processing agreements with processors where the GDPR requires them.</p>

      <h2 class="font-display text-xl font-semibold text-g2-text">Transfers outside the EEA</h2>
      <p>
        Some providers may process data outside the European Economic Area (for example in the United States). Where that
        happens, we rely on GDPR transfer tools such as Standard Contractual Clauses or other approved mechanisms, as
        applicable to the relationship.
      </p>

      <h2 class="font-display text-xl font-semibold text-g2-text">Cookies and similar technologies</h2>
      <p>
        We use technical measures required for the Site to work, to keep it secure, and to operate the contact form. We
        do not run behavioural ad profiling on this Site in a way that would call for a broad, standalone marketing-cookie
        banner today. If we add analytics or marketing cookies later, we will expand this section and provide an
        appropriate consent mechanism under applicable law.
      </p>

      <h2 class="font-display text-xl font-semibold text-g2-text">No solely automated decisions with legal effect</h2>
      <p>
        We do not make decisions about you based solely on automated processing, including profiling, which produce legal or
        similarly significant effects within the meaning of Article 22 GDPR. Anti-spam checks are there to separate bulk
        abuse from genuine human contact, not to build a consumer marketing profile.
      </p>

      <h2 class="font-display text-xl font-semibold text-g2-text">Your rights and complaints</h2>
      <p>Where the GDPR applies, you may have rights including:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>access to your personal data and a copy;</li>
        <li>rectification of inaccurate data;</li>
        <li>erasure or restriction of processing, where grounds exist;</li>
        <li>data portability, where Article 20 GDPR applies;</li>
        <li>objection to processing based on Article 6(1)(f) GDPR, where the legal tests are met;</li>
        <li>withdrawal of consent, where processing relied on consent;</li>
        <li>the right to lodge a complaint with a supervisory authority.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        We may ask for reasonable information to confirm your identity before disclosing or changing records, to reduce the
        risk of unauthorised access.
      </p>

      <h2 class="font-display text-xl font-semibold text-g2-text">Updates to this page</h2>
      <p>
        We may revise this notice when the Site’s features, vendors, or legal requirements change. The current version is
        published at{' '}
        <a href="/en/privacy-policy/" class="text-g2-accent hover:underline">/en/privacy-policy/</a>. For material changes,
        we may add a short notice elsewhere on the Site when that feels appropriate.
      </p>

      <h2 class="font-display text-xl font-semibold text-g2-text">Terms used on this page</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>GDPR</strong> — Regulation (EU) 2016/679 of the European Parliament and of the Council of 27 April 2016.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Controller</strong> — the organisation responsible for the get2software.com Site, as described above.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Site</strong> — the website served under the get2software.com domain, including informational and product
          pages and the contact page with a form when it is enabled.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <p>
        Polish version:{' '}
        <a href="/pl/polityka-prywatnosci/" class="text-g2-accent hover:underline">Polityka prywatności</a>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</MarketingLayout>
